section.para:
Rainfall station name and number;
Rainfall station location in latitude and longitude;
Rainfall station elevation; and
Details of the current instrumentation.
However, for many stations the following meta-data are available also:

listitem.para:
Photos for each of the four main compass points showing
            siting, clearance and proximity to trees, buildings and other
            factors likely to influence measurement of rainfall;

The channel and hydraulic control changing as a result of
            modification due to dredging, bridge construction, or vegetation
            growth;

Backwater effects - changes in the conditions downstream
            such as the construction of a dam or flooding in the next waterway
            downstream;

An interpolation zone where the relationship is within the
            range of the stage measurements used to develop the relationship;
            and

For rod suspension, the standard error ranges from 2% for an
            even, firm, smooth and stable streambed, to 10% for a mobile,
            shifting sand, or dunes streambed;

For cable suspension, the standard error ranges from 2% to
            15% for an unstable streambed, high velocity, and vertical angles;
            and

For acoustic depth measurements, the standard error ranges
            from 2% for a stable streambed to 10% for a mobile, shifting sand,
            and dunes streambed.

Topographic and infrastructure data including structures
          within the floodplain including culverts, bridges, and pipe
          networks;

section.para:


Channel and overland flow path cross-sections (and
              potentially long-sections);




Waterway Structures - weirs and regulators;




Infrastructure - bridges, pipes, pits and culverts;




Road and rail embankments;




Levees; and




Property data (floor level, type of building, size,
              location).

          While it is possible to obtain existing field survey
        data from other sources, it is important to assess its suitability for
        the intended purpose. In other words, it is necessary to obtain both
        the data and the meta-data, which includes items related to date of
        capture, accuracy, etc.

listitem.para:
Areas that are impenetrable from the air (for example, satellites and
                      aeroplanes have difficulty in sensing the ground in areas like the bank of
                      channels and/or heavily vegetated areas);

Sample the entire survey area at a fine resolution - say on a regularly spaced 1
                m Digital Elevation Model (DEM) grid and manually identify important salient
                topographic features and hand enter these features into the models;

section.para:
The Bureau of Meteorology Australian Hydrological Geospatial Fabric (Geofabric
http://www.bom.gov.au/water/geofabric/index.shtml ) consists of a number of GIS layers which include hydrological features such as rivers, water bodies, aquifers, and catchments. The current geofabric includes b1_c4_r31:
Geofabric Surface Cartography - Cartographic representation of surface hydrological features;
Geofabric Surface Network - Network representation of hydrological features;
Geofabric Surface Catchments - Catchment boundaries derived from the 9 second Digital Elevation Model;
Geofabric Groundwater Cartography - Cartographic representation of groundwater hydrology features;
Geofabric Hydrology Reporting Catchments- Contracted nodes, contracted catchments and node-link network; and
Geofabric Hydrology Reporting Regions - Reporting regions based on aggregations of contracted catchments.
